# Valgrind suppressions for the constant-time harness (ct_flows, ct.yml).
#
# Policy (SECURITY_TESTING_ROADMAP.md item 6): a suppression is allowed only
# for a KNOWN, ACCEPTED pattern inside a dependency that we cannot fix at our
# boundary, and every entry must carry a justification. Anything not listed
# here fails the run. Both families below are P-256-only; the
# curve25519-dalek paths run without any suppression.
#
# Verified against curve25519-dalek 4.1.3 / p256 0.13.2 / elliptic-curve
# 0.13.8 / sec1 0.7.3 / subtle 2.6.1 (Valgrind 3.24, aarch64 + x86_64 Linux,
# debug and release), 2026-07-06; re-triaged on CI 2026-07-10 (rustc 1.97.0,
# Valgrind 3.22, x86_64) after a compiler bump changed release inlining.
# Re-triage when bumping these crates or on suppression misses after a
# toolchain drift (ct.yml runs unpinned @stable by design, to catch codegen
# that turns constant-time source leaky — so anchors must be drift-robust:
# prefer a stable, uniquely-named frame over one whose match depends on
# demangled generic-argument ordering).
# Each family is listed for the error kinds observed or plausible across
# codegen (Cond for flag-based branches, Value4/Value8 for tag-indexed
# dispatch), same justification.
#
# Family 1: p256 hash-to-curve internals branch on subtle::CtOption
# discriminants that are invariant-true by construction: the OSSWU map's
# sqrt_ratio always yields a valid root for one of its two candidates, and
# map_to_curve's affine conversion of the mapped point always succeeds —
# `CtOption::unwrap` still executes a hard `assert!` on that (tainted)
# always-true flag. The condition never varies with the secret input, so no
# timing signal exists; the taint is by design (the hash-to-curve input is
# the password). Dependency-internal; cannot be declassified at our boundary.
# Anchored on `hash_from_bytes` (the elliptic-curve hash-to-curve entry, our
# only caller of it) rather than the earlier `*hash2curve*hash_from_bytes*`:
# release inlining collapses osswu/map_to_curve/unwrap and demangles the
# frame as `hash_from_bytes<...::hash2curve::...>`, where "hash2curve" no
# longer precedes the name — so the ordered pattern missed under rustc 1.97.
{
   p256-hash2curve-invariant-ctoption-asserts-cond
   Memcheck:Cond
   ...
   fun:*hash_from_bytes*
}
{
   p256-hash2curve-invariant-ctoption-asserts-value8
   Memcheck:Value8
   ...
   fun:*hash_from_bytes*
}
{
   p256-hash2curve-invariant-ctoption-asserts-value4
   Memcheck:Value4
   ...
   fun:*hash_from_bytes*
}

# Family 2: SEC1 point serialization of a secret-derived P-256 point: the
# sec1 crate dispatches on the encoding's tag byte (`Tag::from_u8` via
# `EncodedPoint::tag/len/as_bytes`) while the point is being encoded —
# before our wire-boundary declassify can run. The tag is 0x04 (a
# compile-time constant) for uncompressed encodings and the y-parity of a
# wire-bound public element for compressed ones; in both cases the
# dispatched value is public by protocol design. Anchored at our two
# serialization helpers so only the encoding path is suppressed.
{
   p256-sec1-tag-dispatch-group-to-bytes-cond
   Memcheck:Cond
   ...
   fun:*P256Group*to_bytes*
}
{
   p256-sec1-tag-dispatch-group-to-bytes-value8
   Memcheck:Value8
   ...
   fun:*P256Group*to_bytes*
}
{
   p256-sec1-tag-dispatch-group-to-bytes-value4
   Memcheck:Value4
   ...
   fun:*P256Group*to_bytes*
}
{
   p256-sec1-tag-dispatch-point-to-bytes-cond
   Memcheck:Cond
   ...
   fun:*oprf_p256*point_to_bytes*
}
{
   p256-sec1-tag-dispatch-point-to-bytes-value8
   Memcheck:Value8
   ...
   fun:*oprf_p256*point_to_bytes*
}
{
   p256-sec1-tag-dispatch-point-to-bytes-value4
   Memcheck:Value4
   ...
   fun:*oprf_p256*point_to_bytes*
}
